Wash and dry all produce. Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Finely chop @Heirloom Grape Tomatoes{4%ounce}. Trim, then thinly slice @Scallions{2}. Mince or grate @garlic{1%clove}. Cut @Fingerling Potatoes{12%ounce} in half lengthwise. Zest @Meyer Lemon{1} until you have 1 tsp zest, then halve. Squeeze 2 TBSP juice into a #small bowl{}.

Toss potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with 1 TBSP @olive oil{1%tbsp} and @Smoked Paprika{1%tsp}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Roast in #oven{} until tender and lightly crisped, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Stir together @Mayonnaise{2%ounce}, @Dijon Mustard{1%tsp}, half the lemon zest, half the lemon juice, and garlic in another small bowl. Season with salt.

Heat @vegetable oil{1%tbsp} in a #large pan{} over medium heat (use a #nonstick pan{} if you have one). Add @Crab Cakes{10%ounce} and cook until golden brown on bottom, about ~{4%minutes}. Add @Butter{1%tbsp} to pan, flip crab cakes, and cook until golden brown on other side, about ~{4%minutes} more.

In a #large bowl{}, toss together tomatoes, half the scallions, remaining lemon juice and lemon zest, a drizzle of @olive oil{3%tsp}, and half the @Arugula{1%ounce} (use the rest as you like). Season with salt and pepper.

Divide crab cakes between plates, then arrange salad on top. Add potatoes to the side and dollop with aioli. Garnish with remaining scallions and serve.

> This recipe keeps the sides simple to let the crab cakes shine: a salad with Meyer lemon dressing and potatoes roasted with smoked paprika.